[
    {
        "content": "<p>I've encountered something that is <em>almost</em> a strict 2-category. <strong>However</strong>, instead of the horizontal composition operator on 2-cells satisfying <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>β</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∗</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo>∗</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>β</mi><mo>∗</mo><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\alpha ; \\beta)*(\\gamma ; \\delta) = (\\alpha * \\gamma);(\\beta * \\delta)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">γ</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03785em;\">δ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">γ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03785em;\">δ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, it only satisfies <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>β</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∗</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≤</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo>∗</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>β</mi><mo>∗</mo><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\alpha ; \\beta)*(\\gamma ; \\delta) \\leq (\\alpha * \\gamma);(\\beta * \\delta)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">γ</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03785em;\">δ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">γ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03785em;\">δ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>If it matters, the 0-cells are all poset enriched, and the ordering on my 2-cells is defined componentwise.</p>\n<p>What sort of thing is an almost-2-category like this? Is this a good reason to abandon my notion of 2-cell?</p>",
        "id": 506717320,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1742388133
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I suspect that one possible answer is that I have an intercategory of some sort, but I'm rather hoping someone knows a simpler answer.</p>",
        "id": 506717991,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1742388305
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd guess that you have yourself a category enriched in the category of 2-categories with the <em>lax</em> (or maybe oplax, haven't checked) Gray tensor product.</p>",
        "id": 506728153,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1742390753
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's recently been <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.08832\">a preprint by Dimitri Ara and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"315471\">@Léonard Guetta</span> </a> developing some of the theory of “Gray-<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ω</span></span></span></span>-categories” which are the version of this where you replace “2-category” with “<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ω</span></span></span></span>-category”.</p>",
        "id": 506728742,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1742390887
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They make a quite strong declaration:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This theorem is an instance of an idea we would like to put forward: every functorial construction on ω-categories should be promoted to a Gray ω-functor.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So if they are correct, things like the one that you are dealing with should be quite naturally occurring.</p>",
        "id": 506729324,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1742391048
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Interesting. Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 506755075,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1742396834
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And having a Gray-category does mean that you have—as you suspected—an intercategory, as Grandis–Paré <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jpaa.2016.08.002\">showed</a> (in section 5) that Gray-categories can be seen as intercategories which are trivial in the transverse and one of the other two directions.<br>\nThe strict Gray-<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ω</span></span></span></span>-categories should also be \"degenerate\" examples of what they call <a href=\"https://cahierstgdc.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/CTGDC_57_2_Grandis-Pare-I.pdf\">chiral multiple categories</a>, but I don't think this has been done anywhere.</p>",
        "id": 506757501,
        "sender_full_name": "David Kern",
        "timestamp": 1742397391
    }
]